  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I get rid of little bumps on my face?",
  "response": "Getting rid of little bumps on your face can depend on the underlying cause. Here are some common types of bumps and general tips to address them:\n\n1. **Acne and Pimples:**\n   - **Cleansing:** Use a gentle cleanser twice a day. Avoid harsh scrubs.\n   - **Topical Treatments:** Consider over-the-counter products containing benzoyl peroxide or salicylic acid.\n   - **Non-comedogenic Products:** Choose makeup and skin care that won\u2019t clog pores.\n\n2. **Milia (Tiny White Bumps):**\n   - **Avoid Picking:** Resist the urge to squeeze them, as this can cause scarring.\n   - **Exfoliation:** Use gentle exfoliants to help remove dead skin cells. Look for products with alpha hydroxy acids (AHAs) or beta hydroxy acids (BHAs).\n   - **Professional Extraction:** A dermatologist can safely remove milia.\n\n3. **Keratosis Pilaris (Small, Bumpy Skin):**\n   - **Moisturizing:** Use a rich moisturizer to hydrate the skin.\n   - **Exfoliating Ingredients:** Look for creams with urea or lactic acid, which can help smooth out the bumps.\n\n4. **Allergic Reactions or Irritated Skin:**\n   - **Identify Triggers:** Pay attention to new products or ingredients that could be causing irritation or allergic reactions.\n   - **Soothing Products:** Use fragrance-free and hypoallergenic skin care products. A cold compress may also help soothe irritation.\n\n5. **Consult a Dermatologist:**\n   - If the bumps persist, worsen, or are causing concern, it\u2019s important to consult a dermatologist who can diagnose the issue and recommend specific treatments, such as prescription medications or procedures.\n\n**General Tips:**\n- Always apply sunscreen during the day, as some treatments can make your skin more sensitive to sunlight.\n- Maintain a healthy diet and stay hydrated to support overall skin health.\n- Avoid touching your face frequently to minimize the transfer of bacteria and oils.\n\nRemember, individual skin types respond differently to treatments, so it might take some time to find what works best for you.",
